    "response_text": "The mean value environmental deviation begins at zero, indicating initial alignment between consumers' environmental values and their milk choices. Over the first five time steps, the metric undergoes a steep, significant increase, rising sharply from zero to approximately 12.6, with the most rapid acceleration occurring between steps zero and four. By step 13, the series reaches its maximum value of 13.48, after which it enters a prolonged plateau phase characterized by stabilization around 13.43. \n\nFrom approximately step 10 through step 32, the deviation exhibits no significant directional trend, maintaining a relatively constant mean of roughly 12.6 while displaying minor oscillations between 13.42 and 13.48. Throughout this plateau period, the system demonstrates six distinct inflection points (at steps 16, 19, 24, 26, 28, and 31), indicating subtle adjustments in the relationship between held environmental values and consumption behaviors, though these fluctuations remain within a narrow band of 0.06 units.\n\nWithin the context of the British milk market transition, this trajectory suggests an initial period where strong incumbent habits surrounding whole milk consumption (initial habit strength of 10.0) create immediate tension with consumers' emerging environmental perceptions regarding alternative milk varieties. The rapid early increase reflects the difficulty consumers face in aligning their choices with their environmental values when confronted with powerful habitual tendencies and social network influences (operating at 30% interaction probability with 20% susceptibility). The subsequent plateau indicates that the system reaches an equilibrium where the persistent force of habit maintenance, combined with social conformity pressures (weighted at 0.28) and moderate social blindness (0.51), sustains a consistent gap between what consumers value environmentally and what they actually choose, settling at a deviation level of approximately 13.4 for the majority of the 31-year simulation period." 

}

